# Capstone linkage for Course 3

For your Course 3 capstone, you can use the Tableau Superstore dataset or a similar public retail dataset. Superstore is bundled with Tableau and has documented fields, making it a dependable teaching dataset, and Tableau explains what makes a “good dataset” for analysis. ([Tableau Help][7]) If you prefer to source alternatives, point learners to Google Dataset Search and teach them to evaluate dataset metadata and licensing before use. ([blog.google][8])

# Alignment with the Google certificate track

This module set mirrors the “Prepare Data for Exploration” outcomes listed by Google, including structured vs unstructured, spreadsheets and SQL, database access, and metadata. ([Career Skills][9])

---

## Quick instructor notes

1. Keep the multi-modal rhythm constant: immersive text, a micro-quiz, narrated slides, then audio dialog that surfaces misconceptions, then the lab. This is the Learn Your Way pattern and is linked to short-term and retention gains in Google’s evaluation. ([Google Research][1])
2. When teaching SQL, anchor examples and clause behavior in PostgreSQL’s official documentation for SELECT, joins, and subqueries. ([PostgreSQL][2])
3. For pivots, reference official help for Excel and the Sheets developer guide if you plan to automate pivot creation for challenge labs. ([Microsoft Support][3])
4. For sampling and metadata, emphasize repeatability and discoverability using ICPSR-inspired elements. ([ICPSR][6])

If you want, I can now spin out the auto-graded items bank and the starter files for the labs as downloadable assets.

